{{Infobox scientist | name = William L. Chameides | native_name = | native_name_lang = | image = <!--(as myimage.jpg, no 'File:')--> | image_size = | alt = | caption = | birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1949|11|21}} | birth_place = [[New York City]] | death_date = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date) --> | death_place = | resting_place = | resting_place_coordinates = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline,title}} --> | other_names = | residence = | citizenship = | nationality = | fields = [[Atmospheric science]] | workplaces = [[Nicholas School of the Environment]], [[Duke University]] | patrons = | alma_mater = [[Binghamton University]], [[Yale University]] | thesis_title = A photochemical theory of tropospheric ozone | thesis_url = http://www.worldcat.org/title/photochemical-theory-of-tropospheric-ozone/oclc/702743961&referer=brief_results | thesis_year = 1974 | doctoral_advisor = J.C.G. Walker | academic_advisors = | doctoral_students = | notable_students = | known_for = [[Global warming]] activism | author_abbrev_bot = | author_abbrev_zoo = | influences = | influenced = | awards = [[James B. MacElwane Medal]] from the [[American Geophysical Union]] (1983)<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Kiang|first1=C. S.|title=1983 James B. Macelwane Awards: William L. Chameides|journal=Eos, Transactions American Geophysical Union|volume=64|issue=31|pages=489|doi=10.1029/EO064i031p00489-01|bibcode=1983EOSTr..64..489K}}</ref> | signature = <!--(filename only)--> | signature_alt = | website = <!-- {{URL|www.example.com}} --> | footnotes = | spouse = Yes | children = Four sons (though one is deceased) and four grandchildren<ref>[https://fds.duke.edu/db/Nicholas/eos/faculty/wlc4/files/CV.pdf Chameides' CV]</ref> }} '''William L. "Bill" Chameides''' (born November 21, 1949 in New York City) is an American atmospheric scientist who was the dean of [[Duke University]]'s [[Nicholas School of the Environment]] from 2007 until July 1, 2014.<ref name=Nature>{{Cite journal | last1 = Gewin | first1 = V. | title = William Chameides, dean, Nicholas School of the Environment and Earth Sciences, Duke University, Durham, North Carolina | doi = 10.1038/nj7158-112a | journal = Nature | volume = 449 | issue = 7158 | pages = 112–115 | year = 2007 | pmid = | pmc = }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.dukechronicle.com/articles/2014/07/01/nicholas-school-welcomes-new-dean-new-building | title=Nicholas School welcomes new dean, new building | work=[[Duke Chronicle]] | date=1 July 2014 | accessdate=4 July 2014 | author=Wang, Grace}}</ref> He is an ISI highly cited researcher,<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20140107110247/http://highlycited.com/names/C.html Highly Cited Researchers with last names beginning with C]</ref> as well as a member of the [[National Academy of Sciences]] and a fellow of the [[American Geophysical Union]].<ref name=Duke/> In December 2013, Chameides announced that he would be stepping down from his position at Duke the following June, saying that he "feels comfortable stepping down now given that he has accomplished many of his initial goals."<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.dukechronicle.com/articles/2013/12/03/chameides-step-down-june-2014 | title=Chameides to step down in June 2014 | work=[[The Chronicle (Duke University)|The Chronicle]] | date=3 December 2013 | accessdate=2 February 2014 | author=Zhang, Ryan}}</ref> He was replaced by Alan Townsend on July 1, but remains a member of the Nicholas School faculty.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.newsobserver.com/2014/05/14/3861285/duke-university-names-new-dean.html | title=Duke University names new dean of environmental studies | work=News & Observer | date=14 May 2014 | accessdate=17 June 2014 | author=Murawski, John}}</ref>
==Education and scientific career== Chameides, a native of New York City, originally wanted to be a lawyer at the time he went to college.<ref name=Nature/> However, he later changed his major, first to physics and then to atmospheric science, as a result of taking an undergraduate physics course.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.bizjournals.com/triangle/stories/2008/06/16/focus1.html?page=all | title=Bill Chameides, Duke University | work=[[Triangle Business Journal]] | date=16 June 2008 | accessdate=2 February 2014 | author=Saraiva, Catarina}}</ref> He received a bachelor's degree from [[Binghamton University]] in 1970, a [[Master of philosophy]] degree from [[Yale University]] in 1973, and a PhD in 1974, also from Yale.<ref name=Duke>{{cite web | url=http://fds.duke.edu/db/Nicholas/faculty/wlc4 | title=William L. Chameides | work=[[Duke University]] | accessdate=2 February 2014}}</ref> He then began [[postdoctoral]] research at the [[University of Michigan]], where he conducted research with [[Ralph J. Cicerone]]. After completing this research, he spent 25 years at the [[Georgia Institute of Technology]], where he eventually became the chairman of the department of atmospheric sciences. While an associate professor there, he was the editor-in-chief of the [[Journal of Geophysical Research]] from 1985 to 1989,<ref>{{cite journal|last=Richman|first=Barbara T.|title=William L. Chameides: New JGR editor|journal=Eos, Transactions American Geophysical Union|volume=65|issue=17|pages=328|doi=10.1029/EO065i017p00328-01|bibcode=1984EOSTr..65..328R}}</ref> and, five years later, was the lead author on a study in ''[[Science (journal)|Science]]'' which reported that [[ozone]] from [[photochemical smog]] may significantly reduce global food production. In the study, Chameides et al. wrote that about 60% of smog is produced in North America, Europe, China, and Japan, which also produce about 60% of the global food supply.<ref>{{Cite journal | pmid = 17778137 | year = 1994 | author1 = Chameides | first1 = W. L. | last2 = Kasibhatla | first2 = P. S. | last3 = Yienger | first3 = J | last4 = Levy h | first4 = 2nd | title = Growth of continental-scale metro-agro-plexes, regional ozone pollution, and world food production | volume = 264 | issue = 5155 | pages = 74–7 | doi = 10.1126/science.264.5155.74 | journal = Science | bibcode = 1994Sci...264...74C }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1994/04/03/us/air-pollution-may-damage-food-supply-in-3-decades.html | title=Air Pollution May Damage Food Supply In 3 Decades | work=[[New York Times]] | date=3 April 1994 | accessdate=2 February 2014}}</ref> In 1998, Chameides was elected into the National Academy of Sciences, becoming the second Georgia Tech professor in the university's history to be so honored (the first was [[Mostafa El-Sayed]] in 1980).<ref>{{cite web | url=https://smartech.gatech.edu/bitstream/handle/1853/41620/1998-05-04_22_15.pdf | title=Second Tech professor elected to National Academy of Sciences | work=The Whistle | date=4 May 1998 | accessdate=2 February 2014}}</ref> In 2005, he left Georgia Tech to become the chief scientist at the [[Environmental Defense Fund]], a decision that Virginia Gewin referred to as "unorthodox." Chameides said he made this decision because he wanted to "...do more to advance the cause of good environmental stewardship."<ref name=Nature/> In 2011, Chameides was the vice-chair of a report issued by the [[United States National Research Council]] entitled "America's Climate Choices."<ref>{{cite book | url=http://www.nap.edu/openbook.php?record_id=12781&page=93 | title=America's Climate Choices: Appendix A | publisher=[[National Academies Press]] | year=2011 | pages=93 | isbn=978-0-309-14585-5}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://content.usatoday.com/communities/sciencefair/post/2011/05/climate-change-global-warming-action-national-research-council-report/1#.Uu6HoHddWUA | title=Risky business: Report says act now to combat climate change | work=[[USA Today]] | date=13 May 2011 | accessdate=2 February 2014 | author=Rice, Doyle}}</ref>
==Public advocacy== Chameides has been active in highlighting the dangers of [[global warming]], and has testified before the [[U.S. House of Representatives]]' Committee on Science, Space and Technology on the matter. In his testimony, delivered on April 25, 2013, he said that global warming is occurring, is primarily caused by human activity, and that it will have many negative effects on the United States, including, but not limited to, "more intense and frequent heat waves, risks to coastal communities from sea level rise, greater drying of the arid Southwest, and increased public health risks."<ref>{{cite web | url=http://docs.house.gov/meetings/SY/SY18/20130425/100766/HHRG-113-SY18-Wstate-ChameidesW-20130425.pdf | title=Hearing on Policy-Relevant Climate Issues in Context | date=25 April 2013 | accessdate=2 February 2014 | author=Chameides, William L.}}</ref> He currently runs a blog on the Nicholas School of the Environment website called "The Green Grok,"<ref>[http://blogs.nicholas.duke.edu/thegreengrok/ The Green Grok]</ref> and has also blogged about global warming and other environmental issues on the [[Huffington Post]]<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/bill-chameides/ | title=Bill Chameides | work=[[Huffington Post]] | accessdate=2 February 2014}}</ref> and for [[Popular Science]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.popsci.com/category/tags/bill-chameides | title=Posts Tagged: Bill Chameides | work=[[Popular Science]] | accessdate=2 February 2014}}</ref> Chameides has also written about the [[economics of climate change mitigation]] for both ''[[Science (journal)|Science]]''<ref>{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1126/science.1138299| title = CLIMATE CHANGE: Carbon Trading over Taxes| year = 2007| last1 = Chameides | first1 = W.| last2 = Oppenheimer | first2 = M.| journal = Science| volume = 315| issue = 5819| pages = 1670 | pmid=17379793}}</ref> and for [[The Guardian]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/cifamerica/2009/oct/15/carbon-emission-convergence-principle | title=A fairer formula for emissions targets | work=[[The Guardian]] | date=15 October 2009 | accessdate=2 February 2014 |author1=Kasibhatla, Prasad |author2=Chameides, Bill }}</ref> Additionally, after [[Joe Bastardi]] claimed on [[Fox News Channel]] that carbon dioxide can't cause global warming because of the [[first law of thermodynamics]] and [[Le Chatelier's principle]], [[Media Matters for America]] contacted Chameides by email, who referred to Bastardi's claims as "utter nonsense."<ref>{{cite web | url=http://mediamatters.org/blog/2011/08/09/a-fox-news-science-lesson/185961 | title=A Fox News Science Lesson | work=[[Media Matters for America]] | date=9 August 2011 | accessdate=2 February 2014 | author=Fong, Jocelyn}}</ref> He has also, along with [[Alan Leshner]], criticized the North Carolina government's proposal of a law in response to a report stating that sea levels were projected to rise about 39 inches over the next century. In an article for the News & Observer, they accused the law's supporters of trying to "disregard projections of sea level rise" and trying to "outlaw climate change."<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.newsobserver.com/2012/08/01/2234915/nc-cant-outlaw-global-climate.html | title=N.C. can't outlaw global climate change | work=[[The News & Observer]] | date=1 August 2012 | accessdate=2 February 2014 |author1=Chameides, William |author2=Leshner, Alan }}</ref> The law, which would prevent the government from using sea-level data based on anything except "historical data" for the next four years, was passed despite Chameides' objections.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://abcnews.go.com/US/north-carolina-bans-latest-science-rising-sea-level/story?id=16913782 | title=New Law in North Carolina Bans Latest Scientific Predictions of Sea-Level Rise | work=[[ABC News]] | date=2 August 2012 | accessdate=2 February 2014 | author=Harish, Alon}}</ref> He has also criticized the [[cash for clunkers]] program by pointing out that, while one of its goals is to decrease CO<sub>2</sub> emissions by promoting the purchase of more fuel-efficient cars, manufacturing new cars results in the production of carbon dioxide—he puts the figure at between 3 and 12 tons per car. He has also calculated that trading in a clunker that gets 18 mpg for a new car that gets 22 mpg would necessitate 5 and a half years of typical driving to offset the car's carbon footprint.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=111511131 | title=Critics Say 'Clunkers' Program Isn't Very Green | work=[[NPR]] | date=3 August 2009 | accessdate=3 February 2014 | author=Joyce, Christopher}}</ref> Chameides has also written about other environmental issues, like chemicals used in certain consumer products. For example, when interviewed by the [[Taipei Times]] about the safety of [[optical brightener]]s in laundry detergent, he said that scientific studies on the topic have been "inconclusive."<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/editorials/archives/2011/01/04/2003492616/2 | title=Going green while pursuing whiter whites | work=[[Taipei Times]] | date=4 January 2011 | accessdate=2 February 2014 | author=Newman, Andrew Adam}}</ref>
